<p>In business and finance, a <b><a href="/wiki/Share_(finance)" title="Share (finance)">share</a></b> (also referred to as <b>equity share</b>) of <b>stock</b> means a share of <a href="/wiki/Ownership" title="Ownership">ownership</a> in a <a href="/wiki/Corporation" title="Corporation">corporation</a> (company). In the plural, <i>stocks</i> is often used as a synonym for <i>shares</i> especially in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>, but it is less commonly used that way outside of <a href="/wiki/North_America" title="North America">North America</a>.<a href="http://www.ldoceonline.com/dictionary/stock_1" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.ldoceonline.com/dictionary/stock_1" rel="nofollow">[1]</a></p>
<p>In the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>, <a href="/wiki/South_Africa" title="South Africa">South Africa</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australia</a>, <i>stock</i> can also refer to completely different <a href="/wiki/Financial_instruments" title="Financial instruments" class="mw-redirect">financial instruments</a> such as government <a href="/wiki/Bond_(finance)" title="Bond (finance)">bonds</a> or, less commonly, to all kinds of <a href="/wiki/Marketable" title="Marketable">marketable</a> <a href="/wiki/Securities" title="Securities" class="mw-redirect">securities</a>.<a href="http://dictionary.cambridge.org/define.asp?key=78290&amp;dict=CALD" class="external autonumber" title="http://dictionary.cambridge.org/define.asp?key=78290&amp;dict=CALD" rel="nofollow">[2]</a></p>
